            "content": "Repair is typically the best choice when: Your faucet is under 10 years old and made by a quality manufacturer (Moen, Delta, Kohler, Grohe), the problem is a worn cartridge or aerator ($150-$300 repair), the faucet body and finish are in excellent condition, replacement parts are readily available, you genuinely like the existing faucet's style and functionality, and repair costs less than 40% of comparable replacement. Example: A 6-year-old Moen Arbor faucet with a dripping handle needs a $180 cartridge replacement. Comparable faucet replacement would cost $750 installed. Repair saves $570 and delivers 8-12 more years of service. This is an obvious repair situation. Red flags suggesting replacement instead: Faucet is 15+ years old with outdated design and limited features, finish is deteriorating or corroded, multiple components are failing simultaneously, repair costs exceed 50% of replacement cost, or you'd prefer updated features like touchless operation or pull-down sprayer."
