            "type": "paragraph",
            "content": "Sink drain leaks cause extensive damage to cabinets, creating warped wood, delaminated particleboard, mold growth, and moisture damage to flooring and adjacent walls—repairs often costing $1,200-$4,500 if leaks continue undetected for months. Leaks typically occur at three locations: the sink flange where drain meets sink bottom (plumber's putty or silicone seal failure), P-trap slip-joint connections (worn washers or loose connections), or tailpiece connections (cracked plastic components or corroded metal). Early detection signs: Musty odors from cabinet interiors, visible moisture on cabinet floors, peeling cabinet finish, or water stains on cabinet sides. Our repair process: We inspect the entire drain assembly identifying exact leak sources, replace worn washers and gaskets at slip-joint connections, re-seal sink flanges with appropriate materials (plumber's putty for metal sinks, silicone for composite or porcelain), replace cracked or corroded drain components, tighten connections to proper torque (hand-tight plus quarter-turn—over-tightening cracks components), and test under full water pressure confirming complete leak elimination. Typical repair costs: Simple washer replacement $95-$150, flange re-sealing $120-$180, complete drain assembly replacement $180-$320. Repairing leaks immediately prevents thousands in cabinet and structural damage—making professional diagnosis and repair extraordinarily cost-effective."
